%S A396297 1,4,12,28,56,104,176,288,448,688,1024,1520,2208,3216,4608,6640,9440,
%T A396297 13520,19136,27312,38560,54928,77440,110192,155232,220752,310848,
%U A396297 441904,622112,884240,1244672,1768944,2489824,3538384,4980160,7077296,9960864,14155152
%N A396297 Construct a planar grid by drawing a square of side 1, and then at each corner, place the midpoint of a square of side 1/sqrt(2), rotated from the first by 45 degs. From each of these four squares continue placing new squares in the same way, each time rescaled by a factor of 1/sqrt(2), as long as they don't overlap any earlier squares. Sequence gives number of squares added at the n-th stage.
%C A396297 Zach Hanks remarks that the illustration was generated by computer, but the terms of the sequence (a(0) to a(7)) were found by hand-counting the cells in the illustration, and should be checked. He also remarks that the structure of this grid is reminiscent of the toothpick structures discussed in A139250 and related sequences. [The eight terms were confirmed by _Rémy Sigrist_.]
%C A396297 From _Rémy Sigrist_, May 24 2026: (Start)
%C A396297 We can compute the sequence using necklaces:
%C A396297 - this method was inspired by A330844,
%C A396297 - we start with the necklace b_1 = (1111) as the starting border,
%C A396297 - a(n) equals the length of b_n
%C A396297         minus the number of occurrences of "10001" in b_n
%C A396297          plus four times the number of occurrences of "10001" in prior borders,
%C A396297 - apply the following substitutions, in this order, to b_n to obtain b_{n+1}:
%C A396297     "10001" -> "0",
%C A396297     "1" -> ">11<",
%C A396297     "0" -> "><",
%C A396297     "<>" -> "0",
%C A396297 - to recreate a border: interpret 0's and 1's as, respectively,
%C A396297   inward corners and outward corners:
%C A396297    - for odd n:
%C A396297                . . . . . |
%C A396297               . . . . . .|
%C A396297                . . . . .1|
%C A396297               . . +------+
%C A396297                . .|0
%C A396297               . . |
%C A396297                . .|
%C A396297    - for even n:
%C A396297               . . . . . . . .
%C A396297                . . + . . . .
%C A396297               . . /0\ . . . .
%C A396297                . /   \ . /
%C A396297               . .     \1/
%C A396297                        +
%C A396297 - in the sequence "10001", the corners corresponding to the two 1's meet;
%C A396297   we merge them into a single "0" and detach the inner square (0000):
%C A396297              |. . . . . . .                   |. .
%C A396297              | . . . . . .                    | . .      . . . . . . . .
%C A396297              |1 . . . . . .                  0|. .      . . . . . . . . .
%C A396297          ----+-------+ . .                ----+ . .      . .+-------+. .
%C A396297         . . 1|      0|. . .              . . . . .      . . |0     0| . .
%C A396297        . . . |       | . .              . . . . . .  +   . .|       |. .
%C A396297       . . . .|       |. . .     ->       . . . . .      . . |       | . .
%C A396297        . . . |       | . .                               . .|       |. .
%C A396297       . . . .|0     0|. . .                             . . |0     0| . .
%C A396297        . . . +-------+ . .                               . .+-------+. .
%C A396297         . . . . . . . . . .                             . . . . . . . . .
%C A396297          . . . . . . . . .                               . . . . . . . .
%C A396297           . . . . . . . . .
%C A396297                                              0
%C A396297                                   0--0      / \
%C A396297 - inner squares alternate between |  | and 0   0,
%C A396297                                   0--0      \ /
%C A396297                                              0
%C A396297 - the squares added at stage n are centered on the border
%C A396297   and prior detached inner squares corners.
%C A396297 (End)
%D A396297 Zach Hanks, Email to N. J. A. Sloane, May 22 2026.
